TY  - JOUR
AU  - Babenko, Ilona
AU  - Bennett, Benjamin
AU  - Sen, Rik
T1  - Regulating CEO Pay: Evidence from the Nonprofit Revitalization Act
PY  - 2026
Y1  - 2026/01/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhaf077
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 39
IS  - 1
SP  - 198
EP  - 252
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This paper examines CEO pay at nonprofits. Using compensation data for 14,111 nonprofits, we find that CEO pay dropped by 2% after legislation in New York reduced CEOs’ ability to influence their own pay. Despite lower pay, CEOs exerted more effort, and nonprofit performance improved. The effects were stronger at commercial nonprofits than at charities and for male CEOs than female CEOs. These findings are consistent with a model where some nonprofit CEOs derive meaning from their work and compensation can be rigged. Overall, our results suggest that regulation that targets the pay-setting process can improve organizational outcomes at nonprofits.
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhaf077
ER  - 




